case_name: Board of Trustees, Ayurvedic and Unani Tibbia College, Delhi & Hakim Mohammad Jamil Khan v. Union of India

facts.text: Petition No. 96 of 1955 filed under Article 32 of the Constitution of India for enforcement of Fundamental Rights.

anchor.surface_text: ORIGINAL JURISDICTION Petition No. 96 of 1955. Petition under Art. 32 of the Constitution of India for enforcement of Fundamental Rights.

facts.text: First petitioner is the Board of Trustees, Ayurvedic and Unani Tibbia College, Delhi, through Hakim Mohammed Jamil Khan, its properly elected Secretary.

anchor.surface_text: The first petitioner is the Board of Trustees, Ayurvedic and Unani Tibbia College, Delhi, through Hakim Mohammed Jamil Khan, stated to be its properly elected Secretary.

facts.text: Second petitioner is Hakim Mohammad Jamil Khan, who states that he is still one of the trustees or members of the said Board.

anchor.surface_text: The second petitioner is Hakim Mohammad Jamil Khan himself, who states that he is still one of the trustees or members of the said Board.

facts.text: Hakim Mohammad Ajmal Khan started a pharmaceutical institute known as Hindustani Dawakhana in 1903.

anchor.surface_text: One Hakim Mohammad Ajmal Khan was a physician  of Unani medicine  of all-India repute. He lived in Delhi and started a pharmaceutical institute in the town known as Hindustani Dawakhana in the year 1903.

facts.text: Hakim Mohammad Ajmal Khan established Tibbia College and died in 1927.

anchor.surface_text: He also established a medical companylege known as the Tibbia College. He died in the year 1927.

facts.text: In 1911, Hakim Mohammad Ajmal Khan along with others formed society Anjuman-i-Tibbia registered under Societies Registration Act, 1860.

anchor.surface_text: But before his death, in the year 1911, he along with certain other persons formed a society styled Anjuman-i-Tibbia and had it registered under the Societies Registration Act, 1860  Act XXI of 1860 .

facts.text: Name of the society changed in 1915 to Board of Trustees, Ayurvedic and Unani Tibbia College, Delhi.

anchor.surface_text: The name of the society was changed in 1915, and it became known as the Board of Trustees, Ayurvedic and Unani Tibbia College, Delhi.

facts.text: Hakim Mohammad Jamil Khan, son of Hakim Mohammad Ajmal Khan, was the first Secretary of the Board.

anchor.surface_text: Hakim Mohammad Jamil Khan son of Hakim Mohammad Ajmal Khan and petitioner number 2 before us, was the first Secretary of the Board.

facts.text: In 1948, Shri Rameshwar Dayal, Dr. Yudhvir Singh and others elected as members; Dr. Yudhvir Singh elected President, Shri Mool Chand Gagerna Joint Secretary.

anchor.surface_text: In the year 1948 Shri Rameshwar Dayal, the then Collector of Delhi, and Dr. Yudhvir Singh the then President of the Delhi Municipal Committee, and certain other persons were elected as members of the Board.

facts.text: On October 18, 1949, suit brought in court of Senior Subordinate Judge, Delhi under S.92 CPC against Secretary and 31 members.

anchor.surface_text: On October 18, 1949, a suit was brought in the companyrt of the senior Subordinate Judge, Delhi under H. 92 of the Code of Civil Procedure against the Secretary and 31 members of the Board.

facts.text: On October 19, 1949, Subordinate Judge appointed two local advocates as joint receivers.

anchor.surface_text: In that suit an application was made for the appointment of a receiver and on October 19, 1949, the Subordinate Judge appointed two local advocate as joint receivers with plenary powers.

facts.text: Receivers took possession of Dawakhana and college between October 19 and 23, 1949.

anchor.surface_text: These receivers took possession of the Dawakhana and the companylege between October 19 and 23, 1949.

facts.text: Delhi State Legislature passed Tibbia College Act, 1952 (Delhi Act No. 5 of 1952), came into force on October 10, 1952.

anchor.surface_text: When the suit was still pending, the Delhi State Legislature passed an Act called the Tibbia College Act, 1952  Delhi Act No. 5 of 1952 , hereinafter referred to as the impugned Act. This Act same into fore on October 10, 1952.

facts.text: By Section 9 of the impugned Act, the old Board stood dissolved and property vested in new Tibia Delhi College Board.

anchor.surface_text: We may only state here that by s. 9 of the impugned Act, the Board stood dissolved and all property, movable and immovable, and all rights, powers and privileges of the Board vested in a new Board companystituted under the Act.

facts.text: Suit before Subordinate Judge withdrawn after passing of impugned Act.

anchor.surface_text: After the passing of the impugned Act, the suit instituted before the Subordinate Judge, the Delhi was withdrawn.

facts.text: Petitioner No.1 moved High Court of Punjab against order giving possession to new Board, unsuccessfully.

anchor.surface_text: Petitioner number 1 unsuccessfully moved the High Court of Punjab against that order.

facts.text: Previous writ petition under Art.32 withdrawn on December 13, 1954.

anchor.surface_text: The respondents to the petition raised a number of preliminary objections, and on December 13, 1954, the writ petition was withdrawn.

facts.text: Fresh election held on January 6, 1955 in accordance with amended rules.

anchor.surface_text: This was followed by some amendments of the rules of the Board and it is stated on behalf of the petitioners that a fresh election was held in accordance with the amended rules on January 6, 1955.

facts.text: Present petition filed on March 14, 1955.

anchor.surface_text: The present petition was then filed on March 14, 1955, in pursuance of that resolution.

holdings.text: The old Board registered under the Societies Registration Act, 1860 is not a corporation.

anchor.surface_text: Our conclusion is that it was not. The most important point to be noticed in this connection is that in the various provisions of the Societies Registration Act, 1860, there are no sufficient words to indicate an intention to incorporate, on the contrary, the Provisions show that there all absence of such intention.

holdings.reasoning_summary: Analysis of Societies Act sections 1-14 shows no intention to incorporate; property vests in trustees/governing body; privileges conferred but no corporate status; precedents like Taff Vale confirm unincorporated status.

holdings.text: A society registered under the Societies Registration Act, 1860 remains an unincorporated society falling under the second part of Entry 32 List II.

anchor.surface_text: A society registered under the Societies Registration Act may have characteristics which are analogous to some of the characteristics of a corporation yet it is not incorporated and remains an unincorporated society. AS soon as it is held that it is an unincorporated society, it must come under the second Part of entry 32 of List II.

holdings.reasoning_summary: Dichotomy in Entry 32 between incorporated corporations (first part) and unincorporated societies (second part); registration confers privileges but no incorporation; even quasi-corporation status does not change unincorporated nature.

holdings.text: The new Board constituted under the Tibbia College Act, 1952 is a corporation with objects confined to Delhi, falling under the first part of Entry 32 List II.

anchor.surface_text: The Board shall be a body corporate having perpetual succession and a common seal and shall by the said name sue and be sued.

holdings.reasoning_summary: Section 3 explicitly creates body corporate; powers/duties under s.7 confined to Delhi institutions; s.9 vests old rights but limited to new Board's purposes in Delhi.

holdings.text: The Tibbia College Act, 1952 is within the legislative competence of the Delhi State Legislature under Entry 32 List II.

anchor.surface_text: the impugned legislation therefore, falls under entry 32 of List II so far as the dissolution of the old Board is concerned, under the second part of the entry and so far as incorporation of the new Board is concerned, under its first part.

holdings.reasoning_summary: Dissolution of unincorporated old Board under second part; incorporation of new Delhi-confined Board under first part; no need for other entries.

holdings.text: The impugned Act does not violate Article 14.
holdings.reasoning_summary: No evidence of other similarly situated institutions; single exceptional institution can form class; follows Sholapur Spinning precedent.

holdings.text: Article 31(2) has no application to the impugned Act.
holdings.reasoning_summary: No compulsory acquisition; merely dissolution of unincorporated society and transfer of management to new board for same purposes.

holdings.text: The impugned Act does not violate Article 19(1)(f) as members have no proprietary right in the property.
holdings.reasoning_summary: Members' rights limited to ensuring charitable use; no beneficial interest per s.14 Societies Act; dissolution right not 'property' under Art.19(1)(f).

holdings.text: Section 22 of Government of Part C States Act, 1951 does not apply to Societies Registration Act, 1860.
holdings.reasoning_summary: Societies Act not made by Parliament (pre-Constitution); s.22 only for repugnancy with Parliament laws; Delhi competent for unincorporated societies.

holdings.text: The impugned legislation is not colourable or mala fide.
holdings.reasoning_summary: Doctrine applies only to competence transgression; legislature competent; motives irrelevant if within power; follows Gajapathi Narayan precedent.

holdings.text: The petition lacks merit and is dismissed.
holdings.reasoning_summary: All challenges rejected; Act valid and no fundamental rights violation.
